                       . Version V0.8 (April 1997) .


 The @{" NewUser " SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/MultiView SCREEN NewUser/Pics/Look-newuser.04"} program is a replacement for NewUser.rexx used by XenoLink

                              @{"  Installation  " LINK "Installation"}
                              @{"    Features    " LINK "Features"}
                              @{"    You need    " LINK "Using"}
                              @{"   Suggestions  " LINK "Suggestions"}
                              @{"   Disclaimer   " LINK "DISCLAIMER"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "10" "10"
@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Using"
@TOC "MAIN"

If you want a fully working program you need the key-file. Without the
key-file, NewUser will not use all the  databases and some lay-out features
are switch off. You can get the key-file on the @{" UBS 6 " LINK "UBS6"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "4" "4"
@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Using"
@TOC "MAIN"

This program needs to write and read files... so make sure it can.
Newuser don't need much free diskspace, only to write some information
about the new user.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "5" "5"
@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Using"
@TOC "MAIN"

NewUser don't need much of your computers memory... i estimated it on 100KB
Make sure you have this free when you start the program. The memory should
be given back when you quit the program.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "6" "6"
@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Using"
@TOC "MAIN"

You don't have to make any extra assignments for this program only make
sure you have the ones i mention (are standard). If you don't have them...
then assign them to were ever you want. Not all assignments are really
nessesary for the program, but when the program cannot locate an assign-
ment then it wil skip that part in the program. But there are some
essential assignments for the program! and the program wil quit, if not
found.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "7" "7"
@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Using"
@TOC "MAIN"

Make sure you have the directories i mention in the list. Not all these
directories are really nessesary for the program, but when the program
cannot locate a directory then it wil skip that part in the program!
But there are some essential directories for the program! and the program
wil quit, if not found.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Using" "Using"
@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Main"
@TOC "MAIN"
Everyting wat is related to NewUser:

@{" 1. " LINK "1"} XenoLink (running)                    essential
@{" 2. " LINK "2"} ARexx (running)                       essential
@{" 3. " LINK "3"} A free-usable Xeno-node               essential
@{" 4. " LINK "4"} Some free RWED-able diskspace         essential
@{" 5. " LINK "5"} At least 100KB free memory space      essential
@{" 6. " LINK "6"} Assignments of below mentioned names  essential
@{" 7. " LINK "7"} Directories of below mentioned names  essential

@{" 8. " LINK "8"} ENV:NUNode                            used for writing & reading, not essential
@{" 9. " LINK "9"} T:NEWUSER                             used for writing & reading, not essential

@{"10. " LINK "10"} S:newuser.key                         used for reading, not essential

@{"11. " LINK "11"} XSCRIPTS:NewUser.rexx                 used for running, essential
@{"12. " LINK "12"} XSCRIPTS:NewUserDoor/NewUser          used for running, essential
@{"13. " LINK "13"} XSCRIPTS:NewUserDoor/NewUser.config   used for reading, not essential
@{"14. " LINK "14"} XSCRIPTS:NewUserDoor/Plaatsen.        used for reading, not essential
@{"15. " LINK "15"} XSCRIPTS:NewUserDoor/Landen           used for reading, essential

@{"16. " LINK "16"} XUTILS:XRoboWriter                    used for running, not essential

@{"17. " LINK "17"} XUSERS:(new user name)/.address       used for writing, not essential
@{"18. " LINK "18"} XUSERS:(new user name)/.password      used for writing, not essential
@{"19. " LINK "19"} XUSERS:(new user name)/.birthday      used for writing, not essential
@{"20. " LINK "20"} XUSERS:(new user name)/.computer      used for writing, not essential

@{"21. " LINK "21"} XUSERS:(your bbs name).txt            used for writing & appending, not essential

@{"22. " LINK "22"} DOORS:NewUsers/NewUsers.LIST          used for writing & appending, not essential

@{"23. " LINK "23"} XMENUTEXT:NewUser.TXT                 used for reading, not essential
@{"24. " LINK "24"} XMENUTEXT:Register.TXT                used for reading, not essential
@{"25. " LINK "25"} XMENUTEXT:ChangeMenuSet.TXT           used for reading, not essential
@{"26. " LINK "26"} XMENUTEXT:ChangeEditor.TXT            used for reading, not essential
@{"27. " LINK "27"} XMENUTEXT:ChangeProtocol.TXT          used for reading, not essential
@{"28. " LINK "28"} XMENUTEXT:ChangeComputer.TXT          used for reading, not essential
@ENDNODE

@NODE "1" "1"
@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Using"
@TOC "MAIN"

This program can only be used within Xenolink. The NewUser.rexx will
be started (normal) when a new user is logged in. So you don't need to
change any configs. NewUser was tested and works perfectly on
XenoLink v1.984 and should also work on other versions. If not...
@{" let me know! " LINK "Suggestions"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "2" "2"
@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Using"
@TOC "MAIN"

An ARexx server running in the background.
Should be normal when you usages Xenolink
@ENDNODE

@NODE "3" "3"
@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Using"
@TOC "MAIN"

This program can be used on different nodes. The NewUser.rexx by this
program should automatically assign you one. For example you run
your bbs on node #1 and node #2 and you get a call from a new user on
a free node #2 the NewUser.rexx will recognize it and write the node
number to an enviroment variable called ENV:NUNode. This way NewUser
can be started in the right node. So you don't need to tell NewUser on
which node you are running. In the normal newuser.rexx you don't need
to do this either but in some doors you do. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE "8" "8"
@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Using"
@TOC "MAIN"

You don't need to have ENV:NUNode it is an environment variable which will
be created by NewUser.rexx. The value of this variable will be the node
number on which a new user has logged in. So don't copy it to ENVARC:
@ENDNODE

@NODE "9" "9"
@NEXT "Main"
@PREV "Using"
@TOC "MAIN"

T:NEWUSER is a temporary file which will be created by NewUser.
This file contains a letter which will be put into your SYSOP-mail Area 1 by
XRobowriter when a new user has logged in. You don't need the file for
the NewUser program.
@ENDNODE

